(280, '2010-09-28 07:09:46', '2010-09-28 07:09:46', 576, '$56 mobile price', '$56-mobile-price', NULL, '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>When someone''s getting all up in your grill, the best thing to say is "You better step off! The surface temperature of grills can approach 550 degrees Fahrenheit&mdash;you shouldn''t be standing on that thing!" Today''s deal demonstrates a high regard for safety by leaving the grilling to the professionals: for $10, you get $20 worth of grilled eats, new American food, and more at Two Rows Classic Grille, located in Allen. Per state law, today''s Groupon is not valid for alcohol purchases.</p>\r\n<p>Family owned, Two Rows Classic Grille synthesizes savory edibles fresh and from scratch in a casual dining and imbibing environment. A sundry selection of creative plates don the <a href="http://tworows.com/pdf/new_Two_Rows_Menu_20x15.pdf">menu</a>, including offerings of grilled meats, sandwiches, pastas, Tex-Mex fare, and brick-oven gourmet pizzas. A starter of fried pickle chips, lightly battered and Cajun-dusted, tickles tongues with delightful dill ($6.79), while the brew house fries ($6.99) reunite displaced fried potatoes with old cheddar and chive chums. Two Rows'' hearty entrees represent the finest tastes of our ecosystem: the piquant sashimi tuna ($12.99) reps the surf, the hickory-smoked honey-glazed pork ribs ($12.99 small rack, $18.99 large) oversee the turf, and the chicken-fried steak ($9.99) upholds the territories of Smurf. Pigthusiasts can also appreciate the porcine polish of a cheddar and honey-pepper bacon burger ($8.29). Cap off a committed consumption session with the pineapple and raisin bread pudding ($4.29).</p>\r\n<p>Friendly, attentive servers constantly roam the floor at Two Rows, mirroring the tender care the restaurant exudes toward its <a href="http://tworows.com/community/index.php">community</a> endeavors. Step inside the welcoming, laid-back grillery for grillicious grill fare, without ever having to deplete your home charcoal silo.</p>', NULL, 2.00, 1.00, 0, '2010-09-28 19:30:00', '2010-09-30 04:30:00', 50.00, 1.00, 1.00, 5, 10, 42464, 53, '<div class="page_content clearfix">\r\n<div class="article description">\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<div>\r\n<p><a href="http://bit.ly/abqkoF">TripAdvisors</a> give Two Rows Classic Grille an average of 3.5 owl eyes. <a href="http://bit.ly/9MGoHI">Yelpers</a> give the restaurant a 3.5-star average, and five <a href="http://bit.ly/cLd4gC">Insider Pagers</a> give the it a three-star average:</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The gourmet brick oven pizzas were excellent. &ndash; <a href="http://bit.ly/abqkoF">JAGIN, TripAdvisor</a></li>\r\n<li>&hellip;there is something remarkable here and that is their home made honey/pepper thick cut bacon. Truly a Texas treasure and they sell it by the pound too! &ndash; <a href="http://bit.ly/c9zfjf">Tres B., Yelp</a></li>\r\n<li>This is a fun place with lots going on, really good food, friendly waiters and waitresses, and reasonable prices. &ndash; <a href="http://bit.ly/cLd4gC">Carroll S., Insider Pages</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n</div>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<div id="voice" class="groupon_voice">\r\n<h2><span style="font-size: x-small;"><span style="font-size: 10px; font-weight: normal;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: 15px;"><strong><br /></strong></span></span></span></span></h2>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', 0, 0, 1, NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2010-09-30 21:30:00', '<ul>\r\n<li>Limit 2 per person. Limit 1 per table. Dine-in only. Not valid with other offers or specials. Not valid toward alcohol.</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.groupon.com/pages/universal-fine-print">See the rules</a><span> that apply to all deals.</span></li>\r\n</ul>', '<ul>\r\n<li>Wide variety of fresh dishes</li>\r\n<li>Delicious honey-pepper bacon</li>\r\n<li>Local, family-owned eatery </li>\r\n<li>Family friendly</li>\r\n<li>Kids menu</li>\r\n</ul>', '<div class="page_content clearfix">\r\n<div class="article description">\r\n<div id="voice" class="groupon_voice">\r\n<h2>Groupon Says</h2>\r\n<div class="groupon_voice_top">\r\n<h3><a href="http://www.groupon.com/groupon_says/campaign-groupon-say-0-13424">America''s Youngest Letter</a></h3>\r\n<p>The letter&nbsp;<em>e</em>&nbsp;is America''s youngest letter, first incorporated in the mid-19th century some 2,600 years after the rest of the Latin alphabet.&nbsp;<em>E</em>&nbsp;quickly rocketed into regular use and in no time was named "America''s Best Letter" in a poll of landowning children who previously could not have even formed the words comprising that title. To capitalize on the letter''s popularity, numerous words added the in-demand grapheme in unnecessary ways, leading to spellings such as "olde," "grille," and "floccinaucinihilipilificatione."</p>\r\n<p><em>E</em>&nbsp;also allowed for the development of the past tense by adding the suffix "-ed" to many verbs. Before this breakthrough, discussion and even thoughts of the past were linguistically impossible, and repeating past mistakes, specifically electing horses to office, was unavoidable.</p>\r\n<p>If you are a quick study, you may have noticed that the previous paragraph has an atypical feature: none of the words contain the letter&nbsp;<em>e</em>. If you take the time to look, you''ll find this isn''t true.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', 0, 0, 0, 9, 0.00, 8.00, 0.00, 0.00, 0.00, 'food ', '', 'http://bit.ly/aDl1s9', 'http://bit.ly/a1AEVE'),
